===Etymology===
From {{etyl|es|en}} {{m|es|anchova}}, from [[Genoese]] {{etyl|lij|en}} {{m|lij|anchua}} {{m|lij|anchova}} or perhaps from a similar {{etyl|co|en}} term. The term's ultimate origin is unclear; some suggest it may have derived from an unattested {{etyl|VL.|en}} term {{m|la|*apiuva}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|aphye}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|ἀφύη}} (which is from a {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} root shared with Sanskrit {{m|sa|अभ्व||monster}}); others suggest it comes from {{etyl|eu|en}} {{m|eu|antxu|antxu, anchu|dried fish}}, from {{m|eu||anchuva|dry}},<ref>{{R:Etymonline}}</ref> if that Basque term is not itself derived from Latin via some intermediary.<ref>Robert Lawrence Trask, ''The History of Basque''</ref>

